e=rb.displayName;const mL=[{q:"How is WPForge different from Local WP or MAMP?",a:"WPForge uses a native Rust/Go architecture with no Electron wrapper, embedded databases, and lazy-loaded services. This means significantly lower memory usage (<100MB idle vs 300-500MB), sub-second boot times, and no background processes draining your battery."},{q:"What does 'zero configuration' mean?",a:"Drop a WordPress zip into WPForge, and it handles everything: extracting files, generating wp-config.php, creating the database, generating secure salts, and configuring the web server. You go from zero to a running site in under a second."},{q:"Do I need MySQL or MariaDB installed?",a:"No. WPForge ships with an embedded MariaDB runtime and also supports SQLite mode — meaning you can run WordPress without any external database service. No background processes, no port conflicts."},{q:"What platforms are supported?",a:"WPForge targets Windows, macOS, and Linux. The first public release will focus on Windows and macOS, with Linux following shortly after."},{q:"Is WPForge free?",a:"The core product is open-source under the MIT license. We plan to offer optional enterprise modules (team workspaces, cloud sync, CI/CD integrations) under a commercial license in the future."},{q:"Can I run multiple WordPress sites simultaneously?",a:"Yes. WPForge's project isolation ensures each site runs in its own sandboxed environment with independent PHP versions, databases, and configurations. Start, stop, and manage them all from the dashboard."},{q:"How do snapshots work?",a:"WPForge can capture the complete state of your WordPress environment — files, database, and configuration — as a lightweight snapshot. Restore to any previous state instantly, or clone environments for testing."},{q:"Can I use my existing WordPress projects?",a:"Absolutely. Point WPForge at any existing WordPress directory, and it will detect the installation, configure the server, and get it running. No migration needed."}],gL